        <section purpose="learnbydoing">
            <title>Learn By Doing</title>
            <body>
                <p>Recall our earlier scenario: The Federal Pell Grant Program provides need-based
                    grants to low-income undergraduate and certain postbaccalaureate students to
                    promote access to postsecondary education. According to the National
                    Postsecondary Student Aid Study conducted by the U.S. Department of Education in
                    2008, the average Pell grant award for 2007-2008 was
                    $2<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T193812-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>600.
                    Assume that the standard deviation in Pell grants awards was $500.</p>
                <wb:inline idref="u3_m4_mean3_tutor1_1" purpose="learnbydoing"/>
                <wb:inline idref="u3_m4_mean3_tutor2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>
            </body>
        </section>

        <example>

            <p>Household size in the United States has
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194659-0500"?>a
                <?oxy_insert_end?>mean
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194701-0500"?>of
                <?oxy_insert_end?>2.6 people<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194710-0500" content=","?>
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194711-0500"?>and
                <?oxy_insert_end?>standard deviation
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194714-0500"?>of
                <?oxy_insert_end?>1.4 people.</p>
            <p>(a) What is the probability that a randomly chosen household has more than 3
                people?</p>
            <p>A normal approximation should not be used here, because the distribution of household
                sizes would be considerably skewed to the right. We do not have enough information
                to solve this problem.</p>
            <p>(b) What is the probability that the mean size of a random sample of 10 households is
                more than 3? </p>
            <p>By anyone's standards, 10 is a small sample size. The Central Limit Theorem does not
                guarantee sample mean coming from a skewed population to be approximately normal
                unless the sample size is large.</p>
            <p>(c) What is the probability that the mean size of a random sample of 100 households
                is more than 3? </p>
            <p>Note: To review how to determine probabilities for z scores, please refer to the
                Standard Normal Table section of the Random Variables module. </p>
            <p>Now we may invoke the Central Limit Theorem: even though the distribution of
                household size X is skewed, the distribution of sample mean household size <m:math
                    overflow="scroll">
                    <m:mover accent="true">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:math> is approximately normal for a large sample size such as 100. Its mean is
                the same as the population mean, 2.6, and its standard deviation is
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194850-0500"?>the
                <?oxy_insert_end?>population standard deviation divided by
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194855-0500"?>the
                <?oxy_insert_end?>square root of
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194859-0500"?>the
                <?oxy_insert_end?>sample size: <m:math overflow="scroll">
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msqrt>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                </m:mrow>
                            </m:msqrt>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msqrt>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                    <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                    <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                </m:mrow>
                            </m:msqrt>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                    <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                    <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                </m:math> The z-score for 3 is <m:math overflow="scroll">
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>6</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mfrac>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                    <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                                    <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                                </m:mrow>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:msqrt>
                                        <m:mrow>
                                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                        </m:mrow>
                                    </m:msqrt>
                                </m:mrow>
                            </m:mfrac>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                            <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>8</m:mn>
                    <m:mn>6</m:mn>
                </m:math> The probability of the mean household size in a sample of 100 being more
                than 3 is therefore P(<m:math overflow="scroll">
                    <m:mover accent="true">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:math> &gt; 3) = P(Z &gt; 2.86) = P(Z &lt; -2.86) = .0021.</p>
            <p>Households of more than 3 people
                are<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194915-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                of
                course<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T194917-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                quite common, but it would be extremely unusual for the mean size of a sample of 100
                households to be more than 3.</p>
        </example>
